## Phase 4 — Component-by-Component Tailwind Migration

> [!NOTE]
> The hardest part. Every Tailwind class that says `text-white`, `bg-white/X`, `bg-[#0a0a0a]`, or `border-white/X` needs a **semantic replacement** so it responds to the theme. Below is the mapping and the files to touch.

### Color Mapping Cheat Sheet

| Dark (current)          | Light equivalent               | Tailwind strategy                          |
|-------------------------|--------------------------------|--------------------------------------------|
| `text-white`            | `text-[var(--color-text)]`     | Replace with `text-text` (custom utility)  |
| `text-white/80`         | darker muted text              | Replace with `text-text-muted` or opacity  |
| `text-white/60`         | medium muted text              | Replace with `text-text-muted`             |
| `text-white/50`         | lighter muted                  | Replace with `text-text-subtle`            |
| `text-white/40`         | very muted                     | Replace with `text-text-subtle`            |
| `bg-[#0a0a0a]`          | `bg-[var(--color-surface-1)]`  | Replace with `bg-surface-1`               |
| `bg-white/5`            | subtle bg lift                 | Replace with `bg-surface-2`               |
| `bg-white/10`           | hover bg                       | Replace with `bg-surface-3`               |
| `border-white/10`       | light border                   | Replace with `border-surface-3`           |
| `border-white/5`        | faint border                   | Replace with `border-surface-3/50`        |

> [!TIP]
> Because the CSS variables are already registered in `@theme {}`, Tailwind v4 auto-generates utility classes like `bg-surface`, `text-text`, `border-surface-3` etc. No extra config needed.

### Files to Update

Each file below uses hardcoded white/dark references. Here's **exactly what** to search-and-replace:

